Happy Thanksgiving if you live in the United States … Happy Thursday if you don’t!

Share below how you’re spending today or a little something you’re grateful for!💗

Happy day to you!

💗Karen

The word “moving” has a double meaning when you’re moving from a home you’ve lived in for over a decade. 
 
It’s a “moving” experience - both emotionally and physically. 

I know because I recently packed up all the belongings I’ve amassed in my life & moved them to a new home.
 
Or rather, Flatrate packed up my belongings for me.  

I decided to hire a moving company to do some of the heavy lifting for me.  

Hmmm… “heavy lifting” also has a double meaning! 
 
Because it not only required physical muscle to put things in the "get rid of pile" and the "new home pile"... it took emotional muscles too. 

I had to tap into my “Inner #MarieKondo” & decide what truly was bringing me joy. 

Let me tell you, I was grateful that @flatrate_moving  was there to assist. 

They became part moving company, part on site therapists, as I decided “yes” or “no” to everything in my old home.
 
As it turns out, I’m not alone in experiencing emotional overwhelm from moving homes.  There’s even a psychological term for this…
 
Relocation Depression

Yes, this is a real thing. It’s defined as an overwhelming & persistent sadness caused by moving… which can even develop into full on #depression.

Perhaps that’s why various studies report that moving is the number one #stressful life event - even listed as more painful than divorce!

What are the most stressful aspects of moving?

Packing:48%
Deciding what to keep vs get rid of/donate: 47%
Making a down payment on new home/getting a mortgage: 28%
 
Did you see that? Moving is doubly more painful than paying for your new home/mortgage! Wild, huh?

Plus 43% of people who did their move all on their own…  said they’d never do that again! I can understand why! 

Let me tell you - I'm so happy I hired Flatrate Moving to not only pack up my stuff in my old apartment… but to unpack everything in my new apartment. It was incredibly relieving to give the major tasks of moving to a reputable moving company. 

Another tip for making it through a big move...

Keep your eye on the prize of enjoying your new home & keep moving forward… one moving box at a time.

xo, Karen

✨Do you have someone in your life who’s behaving badly?

This person might be a family member – or friend – or an ex who remains the parent of your kids.

Thankfully there are things you can do to protect yourself from the drama their toxic behavior creates!

REMINDER:

You need to STOP trying to CHANGE the toxic person into a NON-toxic person!

Instead, you need to START changing how YOU respond to THEM!

I’m here to help!

Grab my research-based psychological tools - which I share in my VIDEO COURSE:

=> Manage & Avoid Drama Llamas! <=

See LINK in my @notsalmon BIO!

LEARN TO…

* Create limits & boundaries to stop toxic people from emotionally manipulating you & pushing your “pissed off” button – so you enjoy life more
* Disarm toxic people – anyone who makes you feel like you’re a prisoner in an abusive relationship! (Feel more calm, focused, productive & happier around them.)
* Stop people from walking all over you – and confidently embrace your self worth
* Learn to NOT go into “reactive mode,” so you reclaim your full power, sense of self & mood
* Manage & avoid “one-sided” relationships, so you enjoy more fulfilling relationships
* Think about toxic people differently, so you don’t allow them to get to you so much
* Do a self-inventory, so you understand your triggers, past programming & communication style
* Know when to walk away – and how best to take these self-loving steps forward

See LINK in my @notsalmon BIO - for more about my VIDEO COURSE “Manage& Avoid Drama Llamas!”

Or head over to notsalmon.com/COURSES

Here’s my tip for you to start 2023 strong!

Many years ago I read an amazing book called “Slowness” by Milan Kundera.

Ironically this was a slender book I sped through in a day!

Kundera explains how we live in a highly speeded-up world.

Our need for speed promotes forgetting.

For example:

* If you want to forget something (aka: a bad memory), you will pick up speed walking down the street.

* If you want to remember something (someone’s name), you’ll slow down your steps.

Kundera warns how speeding up your life keeps you from remembering daily details...

* “Oops! Forgot to pick up blueberries!”

Plus living a busy, fast paced life keeps you forgetful about your overall life values...

* “Ooops! Forgot to be my kindest, best listening self!”

Meaning?

The next time you find yourself racing quickly down the street…. know that you’re not only running to your next appointment.

You are also literally running from contact with your truest feelings… deepest needs … and most valuable insights.

My favorite method for slowing down?

Meditation

When you meditate, you....

* Slow down and remember to live true to your core values.

* See more clearly how to turn your “to do list” into a “to do what matters most” list

* Keep your energy strong… your mind clear… and your soul in the driver’s seat.

So in this new year ahead … make sure you take a little time each day to sit quietly… breathe… meditate.

You will feel calmer… clearer… more confident…. more creative… more productive.

Share below what comes to mind when you read this! Or share your favorite meditation!

AND…If you want to learn a wide range of fun and simple 2 minute meditations and grounding exercises ….which tap into using all your 5 senses… check out my online course “The Anxiety Cure.” 

See link in my @notsalmon bio to learn more!

💗Karen

Do you have someone in your life – who is behaving badly?

This person might be a family member – or friend – or an ex who remains the parent of your kids.

Thankfully there are things you can do to protect yourself from the drama they create!

BIG REMINDER: You need to STOP trying to CHANGE the toxic person into a NON-toxic person!

Instead, you need to START changing how YOU respond to THEM!

I’m here to help!

Grab my research-based psychological tools - which I share in my …

➡️ Manage and Avoid Drama Llamas Online Course!

See LINK in my @notsalmon BIO for more info about my boundaries training!

Already these tools have helped many people around the world to disarm toxic people & reduce conflict, stress & drama.

LEARN HOW TO…

* 	create limits & boundaries to stop toxic people from emotionally manipulating you and pushing your “pissed off” button – so you enjoy your life more
* 	disarm toxic people – anyone who makes you feel like you’re a prisoner in an abusive relationship! (Feel more calm, focused, productive & happier around them.)
* 	stop people from walking all over you – and confidently embrace your self worth
* 	learn to NOT go into “reactive mode,” so you reclaim your full power, sense of self & mood
* 	manage & avoid “one-sided” relationships, so you enjoy more fulfilling relationships
* 	think about toxic people differently, so you don’t allow them to get to you so much
* 	do a self-inventory, so you understand your triggers, past programming & communication style
* 	know when to walk away – and how best to take these self-loving steps forward

💔If someone hurt you deeply to your soul, it’s tempting to want to shut down and shut off – to give in and give up – to get bitter, resentful, depressed – and all before breakfast!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This soul-shutting-down tendency reminds me of classic zombie horror movies. 

You know, where unconscious, soulless zombies walk around in darkness, taking bites out of innocent, happy, soulful people?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
One chomp, then these newly bitten folks find themselves becoming zombie-like themselves.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
They feel their souls shut down.  They crave spending time in darkness. They want to bite others.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Likewise, if you’ve suffered from an emotional zombie bite... it’s temping to want to join the zombie crowd.... and shut off your soul...seek dark thoughts... and chomp upon another.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s especially tempting to wanna chomp upon the zombie chump who chomped upon you!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But you must resist. You must stay strong. You must keep your soul alive!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
How? First, you must face toward the light - where love, forgiveness, inner peace, faith, joy, and growth can all be found. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Zombies can't survive in the light.  Zombies thrive in darkness with a shut-down soul.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
One the biggest sources of light:  Self-love. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
One of the biggest sources of self-love: Forgiveness.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Forgiveness can start with forgiving yourself for being bitten by a soulless zombie.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
After all, chances are, the zombie who chomped upon you didn’t look like a zombie at the time.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Often these soulless zombies pass themselves off as normal soulful people.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Next you have to forgive the zombie who bit you. This will release their poison from your system.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
How to forgive? Remind yourself that your zombie probably became a zombie because a zombie bit them. And the zombie who bit them was bitten by a zombie, etc 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Feel compassion for these zombies, each walking the earth with a shut-down soul.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Vow to yourself that you will do what you can to save this planet from being overtaken by zombies, by making sure you, won’t become a zombie yourself!

Below are 10 warning signs a person might be toxic:

1. They cause a lot of drama, conflict, stress and/or sadness.
2. You feel like you’re walking on eggshells around them. They don’t make you feel “emotionally safe.”
3. You give more than get. You feel used.
4. They belittle you. You feel judged and disrespected when you talk to them.
5. You feel they talk sh*t about you behind your back.
6. You don’t like yourself when you’re with them.
7. You feel manipulated or controlled by them. They make you say or do things you don’t want to say or do.
8. You no longer trust them. You feel they’re lying or hiding something. They “gaslight” you when you confront them.
9. You don’t think they have good intentions. You feel like they want to see you do badly.
10. You feel a knot in your stomach whenever you see they called or texted.

Share below what comes to mind when you read this.

If you feel one or more of the above might apply to someone in your life, well...you might be dealing with a toxic person.

If you need support to manage and heal from a toxic relationship… see link in my @notsalmon bio for a range of resources.

* Manage & avoid “one-sided” relationships, so you enjoy more fulfilling relationships
* Think about toxic people differently, so you don’t allow them to get to you so much
* Do a self-inventory, so you understand your triggers, past programming & communication style
* Know when to walk away & how best to take these self-loving steps forward

💗The older I get the more I trust and honor my gut instincts! You too?

Strong intuition can protect you from bad people and bad situations!

Basically, your intuition works like a compass - alerting you to where you need to go - or NOT go.

Plus when you listen to your “gut instincts” (or “spirit guidance” - whatever you might call it) - then you wind up making better daily choices - and feeling more confident about what you choose to say and do.

Unfortunately, your intuition can get blocked by a range of things:

* fear & worry
* self-doubt & insecurity
* outside pressure from others
* disbelief that intuition is “real”

As a result, you ignore your hunches, instincts, red flags, street smarts - and that feeling of “knowingness”

Being calm is good. But feeling triggered has a message for you. 

Some strategies for when you're triggered...

1. When you notice yourself feeling a strong emotional reaction, stop to consider what just happened & what activated your response.

2. Bravely tap into detective mode. Ask yourself: When have you had this reaction before? Follow your feelings back to their origins - and try to find the initial event, trauma, wound.

3. Look for patterns. For example, when other people share about a happy relationship moment... or ask you lots of questions about your love life... do you feel triggered because you have fears about being all alone...or because you have abandonment issues from your childhood... or because your parents ignored you... or divorced?

4. Do your best to own your feelings. Give yourself permission to feel sad, angry, fearful, jealous, resentful. You need to first own your feelings - before you can disown them. Denying or ignoring what you feel will simply make you feel worst over time. 

5. After you own how you feel, then do the work of disowning. Remind yourself that although you experienced pain in the past, those specific circumstances are NOT repeating now in this moment. THIS is not THAT. Then mindfully ask yourself, "What's another perspective I can choose? What's another response I can choose?"

6. Communicate how you feel. If someone triggered you, share how you feel - so the situation doesn't repeat itself. Breathe. Get calm. Use "I feel" statements.

6. Don't just work on "short-term coping strategies." Work on "long-term healing." Journal about the root causes of your triggers & try to heal these wounds.

IDEAS TO HELP: When I’m in the midst of overthinking, I do a few things.

1. I ask myself if I’ve thought this thought before - and if so - if I’ve gleaned the lesson, insight, solution from it...?

2. If it’s an old worry, I remind myself that I’ve chewed the flavor out of this worry - and to refocus instead on something positive ...or simply meditate/breathe.

3. If it’s a new thought/worry- I focus on what aspect of the issue I can control - or what helpful insights or solution I might find.

4. I remind myself: an hour of worry is even more exhausting than an hour at the gym - and so it’s essential to let the worry go! Next I either re-focus on something proactive I can immediately do to change the situation - or re-focus on something I can immediately do to bring myself joy or inner peace!

💦💧 How many glasses of water do you drink a day? 👇Share below!

🤓Fun facts: Want to become 3 times more likely to feel “very happy?”

Then I recommend you stop seeing your glass of water as half full. 

Start seeing it as completely empty—because you’ve sucked that baby down!

Translation: You gotta drink a lot of water - because drinking water makes you feel happier! 

A study by O. Vine reports:

*80% of people who reported drinking ten or more glasses of water daily were the most likely to say they were “very happy.”

*20% of those who said they “didn’t drink enough water” said they’re “very happy.”

So if you want to be happier... don’t just focus on positive thinking. 😉

Focus on positive drinking.💦

Easier said than done? 

Here's some tips to help you get it done!

1. Carry a water bottle with you wherever you go. This makes it easy to sip on water throughout the day, no matter where you are.

2. Set reminders for yourself to drink water. You can use an app or alarm on your phone... or a sticky note on your computer.

3, Infuse your water with some fresh fruit or herbs for a little extra flavor. 

4. Try to drink the same amount of water at the same times each day, so you're more likely to embrace drinking water as a habit.

I raise my glass of water in toast to you - wishing you a good mood and good health!

xo, Karen

Age? Pfft! It's just a number! 

Hell, at 62, I'm not getting older—I'm getting bolder! 💃

You see, with each passing year, I'm more in touch with who I am, more in tune with what I want for my life. 

I'm not here to fade into the background!  I'm here to make some noise and rattle some cages. 🔥

I've come to realize that youthfulness isn't about the wrinkles on our faces... or the years we've stacked up. Youthfulness is about that fire in our souls... and that unyielding belief that life is meant to be lived at the fullest... no matter your age! 🌟

So, let's celebrate the wisdom we've gained along the way... and use it to light up the world... to inspire others... and to keep pushing boundaries like the badass renegades we are. 🌈

Age ain't got nothin' on us. We're here, we're strong, and we're just getting started. 

Thoughts?

💖Karen

REMINDER: I know life has an uncanny ability to test our resolve and hurl obstacles in our path. 

And so it's tempting to get caught up in the darkness and let the cynicism take over. 

But it is precisely during our challenges that we must hold onto the belief that beauty can find its way into our life. 

And it can.

It might be a chance encounter, a serendipitous moment, a random act of kindness from a stranger, or even a longed for dream coming true that reminds you that, YES, all is possible!

So keep your eyes wide open for those miracles, both small and LARGE. 

Who knows what surprises are just around the corner, waiting to delight you? 

You have every reason to believe that the best is yet to come.

👇Drop a 💗below if this resonates - then do what you can to drop your painful memories.

HOW TO LET THAT SHIT GO...

🌟 Reframe your past.. so you can release its grip, and embrace a brighter future! 

1️⃣ Acknowledge: Recognize that your past doesn't define you. It's a collection of experiences, but it doesn't determine your worth or potential.

2️⃣ Learn and Grow: Extract the valuable lessons from your past without dwelling on the pain. Use them as stepping stones for personal growth and wisdom.

3️⃣ Practice Forgiveness: Forgive yourself and do you best to forgive others. Holding onto grudges or guilt only prolongs the negative impact. 

4️⃣ Embrace Self-Compassion: Treat yourself with kindness and understanding. Understand that mistakes are part of being human. Be gentle with yourself as you navigate through the process of letting go.

5️⃣ Live in the Present: Focus on the present moment and all the opportunities it holds. Redirect your energy towards creating a fulfilling and joyful life right now.

6️⃣ Create a New Narrative: Rewrite your story and shape it in a way that empowers you. Replace self-limiting beliefs with positive affirmations that reflect your true potential.

7️⃣ Let Go: Release the grip of the past by consciously choosing to let it go. Allow yourself to move forward, unburdened by what no longer serves you.

Remember, the power to redefine your future lies within you. 🌈 

xo, Karen

REMINDER: Growing up is often seen as something we only do in childhood... BUT the truth is... we continue to grow and change throughout our lives. 

We're constantly encountering new challenges, facing new questions, and discovering new facets of ourselves. 

And that's a beautiful thing.

Of course, growth isn't always easy. 

Sometimes it's painful, messy, and uncomfortable. 

We have to confront our fears, our limitations, and our mistakes. 

We have to be willing to try new things, to take risks, and to make mistakes. 

We have to be humble enough to admit when we don't know something, and curious enough to keep seeking answers.

But the rewards of growth are immense. 

When we embrace the fact that we're always becoming, we open ourselves up to a world of possibilities. 

We become more resilient, more adaptable, and more compassionate. 

We learn to be patient with ourselves and others, and to appreciate the journey as much as the destination.

So let's embrace our status as "growing ups." 

Let's celebrate the fact that we're never too old to learn something new, to try something different, or to be surprised by what we're capable of. 

Let's keep pushing ourselves to grow... and compassionately support each other along the way.

xo, Karen

In fact... numerous studies have reported that "conscious breathing techniques" have a profound benefit on our mental well-being. 

One study by researchers at Stanford University revealed that "deliberate deep breathing exercises" can significantly reduce symptoms of anxiety and stress. 

Why? "Deliberate deep breathing" winds up triggering a relaxing cascade of physiological changes that shift your nervous system from fight-or-flight mode to a state of calm and balance. 

It's like pressing a reset button for your mind and spirit. 🔄💆‍♀️

So next time you're feeling stressed... take a moment to pause.... inhale deeply...and exhale slowly... so you activate your body's relaxation response. 

In fact... take a deep breath NOW... embrace this present moment, and let the peace within you guide your way. You got this!

If you're struggling with accepting that you should break up with someone... or if you recently broke up with someone... I've got some insights and strategies to help you. 

First let me say... I understand how painful it feels to move on from someone you loved.

According to psychologists, the trauma a break up causes can lead to symptoms similar to PTSD. 

I felt this pain myself after my breakup with my "Prince Harming," and it had a devastating ripple effect in my life. 

The fear of being alone haunted me, leading me to jump from one relationship to another. 

And when I did date someone seriously, I was nervous about having my heart trampled upon again. 

Please know that you're not alone in the pain you're feeling. 

The important question to ask yourself: What do you do with that pain? 

Do you allow it to paralyze you?

Or do you learn from it & become stronger, wiser, happier? 

As the famous saying goes, 'We repeat what we don't repair.' 

That's why I've created my "Broken Heart Recovery Online Course." 

(See LINK in my BIO!)

It's designed to help you do the deeper work necessary to heal your pain, repair your subconscious beliefs, and recognize your self-worth. 

With my "Broken Heart Recovery Online Course," you'll gain the insights, support, and tools needed to find a loving partner who respects and prioritizes you. 

In fact...I created my happy family life thanks to all the insights & strategies inside this course!

As soon as you sign up for the Broken Heart Recovery Online Course, you'll gain instant, lifetime access to these proven tools ... that you can watch at your own pace on any screen device. 

Remember, wherever you go, there you are. If you keep doing what you've always done, you'll get the same results.

It's time to show yourself some extra love & put in the work to both heal & repair... so you can break free from the patterns of your past ....and FINALLY experience the best relationship of your life. 

YES... it's possible!!

🌟 5 Steps to Clear Your Mental Clutter! 🧹✨

1️⃣ Acknowledge What's Out of Your Control: Identify the thoughts and worries that are beyond your control. Recognize that dwelling on them only drains your energy.

2️⃣ Embrace the Power of Letting Go: Practice acceptance and release what you can't control. Understand that it's okay to redirect your focus towards more productive and positive thoughts.

3️⃣ Engage in Mindful Activities: Engross yourself in activities that bring you joy and create a sense of flow. Whether it's painting, dancing, or hiking in nature, find what helps you detach from unhelpful thoughts.

4️⃣ Journal Your Worries Away: Write down your concerns, fears, and frustrations. This act of externalizing your thoughts can provide clarity and free up mental space for more constructive thinking.

🌟 Take a Seat and Recharge 🌟

1️⃣ Find a calm spot: Seek out a serene corner where you can escape the noise and distractions. It could be your favorite chair, a cozy nook, or a peaceful park bench.

2️⃣ Set the scene: Create an ambiance that promotes relaxation. Dim the lights, light a scented candle, or play soothing music to help you unwind.

3️⃣ Close your eyes, take a deep breath: Inhale deeply, feeling your lungs expand, and exhale slowly, releasing any tension or worries. Focus on the present moment, letting go of past regrets and future concerns.

4️⃣ Embrace gratitude: While you sit and breathe, take a moment to express gratitude for the blessings in your life. Reflect on the positive experiences and people who bring you joy.

Plus here's some steps to help...

1️⃣ Focus on what you can control: In challenging times, it's crucial to redirect your energy towards the things within your control. Shift your focus to actions and choices that empower you.

2️⃣ Seek support: Reach out to your trusted tribe. Surround yourself with people who uplift and inspire you.

3️⃣ Practice radical acceptance: Acceptance doesn't mean resignation; it means acknowledging reality as it is... while also finding the strength to move forward... believing in your heart that every step forward is a step to a brighter future.

4️⃣ Cultivate self-compassion: Be kind to yourself during challenging times. Treat yourself with the same empathy and understanding you would offer a close friend. Nurture your well-being through self-care practices that replenish your mind, body, and soul.

👇BELOW are 5 tips to start chiseling away what's not serving you - so you can showcase the true goddess you are!👇

1. Meditate daily: This is your chisel. It helps you become more aware of the thoughts and habits that aren't serving you and allows you to consciously start to change them.

2. Visualize the Goddess You Want to Be: Picture yourself as the goddess you aspire to be. This is your blueprint. By continually visualizing this version of yourself, you start to align your actions with that vision.

3. Cultivate Gratitude: Focus on the aspects of yourself that you love and appreciate. This gratitude can help elevate your mood and provide the motivation you need to continue chiseling away the parts of yourself that aren't working.

4. Believe in Your Unlimited Potential: Always remember that your capacity for growth and change is limitless. This belief is your hammer, giving you the strength to chip away at the old you and reveal the goddess within.

5. Live in the Present: Your transformation is happening now, not in the past or the future. By focusing on the present moment, you can take the necessary actions to shape yourself into the person you want to be.

Share your thoughts on this below!!

xo, Karen

BELOW is a 5-step guide to tap into discipline... Comment below which of these 5 steps you struggle with most - and I'll see if I can help you further!

1. Define Your Goals: Start by defining what you want clearly. Vague goals lead to vague outcomes. So, get specific.

2. Break It Down: Big goals can be intimidating. Break them down into bite-sized tasks. Think of them as the rungs on your ladder to success.

3. Prioritize: Not all tasks are created equal. Prioritize based on impact. The high-impact tasks? They go to the top of your list.

4. Set a Schedule, Not a Deadline: Deadlines breed anxiety. Schedules? They breed productivity. Don't just set a target date; instead, allocate time each day to work towards your goal.

5. Embrace the Suck: No journey of discipline is all sunshine and rainbows. There will be tough days. Embrace them. Remember, they're part of the process.

And voila, there you have it - your roadmap to discipline. Strap in, gear up, and get ready to climb!

xo, Karen

Drop some 💝💖💗 for following your heart!

MY STORY: About 2 decades ago I used to joke that for me all dating should be re-named "blind-dating” – and instead of saying I was “seeing someone right now” – I should be more honest, and say, “I’m dimly viewing someone."

I'd say this as a joke - because it seemed the men I was dating regularly turned out to be total heartbreakers.

Well, today I want to reveal something very embarrassing.

Ready?

I wasn't actually "dimming viewing" these men.

In fact...I was seeing them rather clearly!

Often I'd know right away...on our first few dates... that the guy was gonna turn out to be a total "Prince Harming."

I'd get this "feeling."

Yet I'd continued to date the guy anyway.

I'd simply ignore my gut instincts!

Why?

* I didn't listen to my intuition - because I didn't trust my intuition!

Eventually I had enough pain & heartbreak - and I vowed to myself that I would learn how to hone and trust my gut instincts!

So I hunkered down & researched everything I could about how to develop and strengthen my inner guidance system.

I discovered some helpful exercises, journal prompts, games, tools etc...which helped me to develop and sharpen my intuition to a powerful degree.

Eventually, I became what psychologists call "a high intuitive."

As a result I stopped constantly asking friends and family their opinions on what they thought about a person or situation.

Instead I became my own expert opinion on managing my life!

I began regularly tapping into my gut instincts - so I always felt confident about what I should say and do.

Sure enough... when I started to listen to my gut instincts more, I began making MUCH better life choices.

And that’s when I created my happy family life I enjoy today!

I now 100% believe if you want to live your best life, then you must include your "inner wisdom" as an important perception that you honor and harness.

I believe so much in the power of gut instincts that I created a SELF PACED ONLINE PROGRAM..

> Develop Stronger Intuition Course

See link in my bio to learn more!

xo, Karen

Drop some 🛑⛔️🚫 for the power of pause.

Many years ago I read an amazing book called “Slowness” by Milan Kundera.

Ironically this was a slender book I sped through in a day!

Kundera explains how we live in a highly speeded-up culture.

Our need for speed promotes forgetting.

For example:

* If you want to forget something (aka: a bad memory), you will pick up speed walking down the street.

* If you want to remember something (someone’s name), you’ll slow down your steps.

Kundera warns how speeding up your life keeps you from remembering daily details...

* “Oops! Forgot to pick up blueberries!”

Plus living a busy, fast paced life keeps you forgetful about your overall life values...

* “Ooops! Forgot to be my kindest, best listening self!”

Meaning?

The next time you find yourself racing quickly down the street…. know that you’re not only running to your next appointment.

You are also literally running from contact with your truest feelings… deepest needs … and most valuable insights.

My favorite method for slowing down?

Meditation

When you meditate, you....

* Slow down and remember to live true to your core values.

* See more clearly how to turn your “to do list” into a “to do what matters most” list

* Keep your energy strong, your mind clear & your soul in the driver’s seat.

So … make sure you take a little time each day to sit quietly… breathe… meditate.

You will feel calmer… clearer… more confident…. more creative… more productive.

Drop a 💓 to commit to mindfully seeing things as they are - and protecting yourself from triggers from your past.

How? Here are 8 steps to follow...

1. When you notice yourself feeling a strong emotional reaction..stop to consider what just happened and what activated your response.

2. Bravely tap into detective mode. As yourself: When have you had this reaction before? Follow your feelings back to their origins - and try to find the initial event, trauma, wound.

3. Look for patterns. For example, when other people share about a happy relationship moment... or ask you lots of questions about your love life... do you feel a triggered because you have fears about being all alone...because of an abandonment issue from your childhood... or because your parents ignored you... or divorced?

4. Do your best to own your feelings.  Give yourself permission to feel sad, angry, fearful, jealous, resentful.  You need to first own your feelings before you can disown them. Denying or ignoring what you feel will simply make you feel worst over time.

5. After you own how you feel, then do the work of disowning. Remind yourself that although you experienced pain in the past, those specific circumstances are NOT repeating now in this moment. THIS is not THAT.  Then mindfully ask yourself, "What's another perspective I can choose? What's another response I can choose?"

6. Communicate how you feel - calmly. If someone has triggered you, sharing how you feel can help you to avoid a similar situation repeating itself. Breathe. Get calm. Use "I feel" statements.

7. Don't just work on "short-term coping strategies." Work on "long-term healing." Journal about the root causes of your triggers, and try to heal these wounds. 

8. Consider working with me 1-on-1 as your Mindset Mastery Coach. (Over the last few decades, I have helped many thousands of clients heal their emotional wounds and stop allowing triggers to impact them.) See link in my @notsalmon bio!

I don't know about you, but I'm so over restrictive diets that make us feel like we have to give up all our favorite foods in order to be our healthiest weight. And research actually shows that restrictive diets can lead to increased cravings and binge eating.

Plus, depriving ourselves of the foods we love can seriously make us feel cranky! 

That's why I'm all about finding a way to indulge in my favorite foods - in moderation.  To help do this, I’ve been using innovative techniques - like starting my meal with protein, using smaller plates, sipping on tea before a meal, and experimenting with spices that reduce sugar cravings. 

I share all about this —and more - in my self paced online program: The Stop Emotional Eating Course - where I offer a range of mindful and intuitive eating strategies! 

See link in my bio!

Oh - and below is my favorite-est Rumi poem - which has helped to console me during tough times - so - hoping it might offer comfort for you too.

GUEST HOUSE
by Rumi

This being human is a guest house.
Every morning a new arrival.
A joy, a depression, a meanness,✨some momentary awareness comes✨as an unexpected visitor.
Welcome and entertain them all!✨Even if they are a crowd of sorrows,✨who violently sweep your house✨empty of its furniture,✨still, treat each guest honorably.✨He may be clearing you out✨for some new delight.✨The dark thought, the shame, the malice.✨meet them at the door laughing and invite them in.✨Be grateful for whatever comes.✨because each has been sent✨as a guide from beyond.

Life is too short and your energy too precious to squander it. 

Here's a 2-step tip to use your energy wisely:

1️⃣ Evaluate: Every morning, look at your "to do list" and take a moment to really think about the power and worth of your energy. Think about what and who matters most to you. Think about your core values and biggest goals/dreams. Then learn to say that tongue twister of a word “no”!! Remember, you're not an unlimited cell phone plan. 📱

2️⃣ Prioritize: As new things come up throughout your day ... pause... and really think about where and with whom you want to focus your energy. Be as picky with your time as you are when you pick that perfect avocado at the grocery store. 🥑

xo, Karen

I don't know who said this quote- but I love it - so I designed this poster for it.

I’m gonna be 63 years young in August - and - I’m here to tell you -  I believe there are some definite benefits to growing older – besides the discounted movie tickets.

In fact - I'm a bigtime research geek - so I've been researching the benefits of growing older - and I found the following interesting study.

COOL STUDY ON AGING:

Dr. Gene Cohen - a neuroscientist - explored the “amygdale” of older aged people versus younger people. 

The “amygdale” is the part of the brain that processes emotions.

Dr. Cohen wanted to see if young people and old people were similarly able to process negative emotions.

Guess what? 

Dr. Cohen found that older people were better able to process negative emotions versus younger people. Yep. Older people's amygdala wound up lighting up less intensely and for a shorter interval when dealing with things like fear, rage and envy.

Meaning?

As you get older, you might indeed get wiser – because you might not let things get to you as much or for as long.

As Cohen says: “I think that after 50 there’s a new senior moment—a creative moment, characterized by your inner voice saying, ‘What can they do to me?’”

I gotta say, I personally relate to Cohen’s findings. 

I’ve found that as I’ve gotten older I don’t get as upset by things.

Maybe it’s because I’ve witnessed many times by now how “this too shall pass”is a true story.

Plus…maybe it’s because I’ve gained confidence overtime that whatever challenging event happens to me, I have the inner ability to handle it.

After all, I’ve survived 100% of the tough times in my life – and that’s a pretty good track record to have.

Thoughts? Share below!

xo, Karen

REMINDER: Finding your inner power sometimes requires a journey through the shadows.✨

💫 Here's a 3-step resilience builder:

1️⃣ Feel it: There's no point in denying or repressing your pain. Embrace the hurt. Let your feelings flow through you. This isn't a sign of weakness, it's a step towards growth.

2️⃣ Understand it: Once you've allowed yourself to feel, the next step is to understand your pain. What triggered it? What can it teach you about yourself and your limiting beliefs, vulnerabilities and patterns? 

3️⃣ Transform it: Finally, convert this understanding into action. What changes can you make? How can you turn this crisis pain into crisis fuel - and vow to make sure this pain does not repeat itself again in another situation? 

Remember: 'First it hurts. Then you find a strength that you didn't know existed within you.' It's not just a quote. It's a journey from surviving to thriving.💫✨

xo, Karen

You know, there's a sneaky trick life plays on us sometimes. 

It can convince us that a crummy situation is, well... just the norm. 

We're tough cookies, right? 

We can handle it. 

So we stay, even though it's doing us no good.

And before we know it, we're watching our best years waving us goodbye from the rearview mirror.

Here's a little hard-earned wisdom for you: 

Recognize when it's time to pack up your bags. 

Easier said than done, I know. But try this. 

Each day, ask yourself : "Is this situation serving me, or am I serving it?" 

Remember: You're not a servant to your life! You're the CEO of your life!!

Finding it tough right now to take charge of a tough situation? That’s okay. I've been there myself. 

And that's why I created my therapist recommended online program: "The Broken Heart Recovery Course." 

The insights and strategies inside of "The Broken Heart Recovery Course" helped me to break free from painful patterns and create the happy family life I have today.

Plus my techniques were so loved by Oprah and Psychology Today that they each gave me a column on their site!

So I gathered together the BEST of my strategies - and added some new ones - and produced videos with everything - where I am talking to you - as if we're having coffee together! Everything is inside my " Broken Heart Recovery Course!"

The soul of you.

The you that gets super excited about vintage vinyl records.... or can cook a mean spaghetti bolognese. 

The you that's secretly a rockstar in your shower concerts... or has an unquenchable curiosity for the mysteries of the universe.

The you that stands firm for honesty, even when it's inconvenient... and laughs heartily at goofy dad jokes ...because humor doesn't always have to be sophisticated. 

The you that can debate passionately about your favorite movies... or is always up for an impromptu road trip adventure.

The you that becomes a child again when you're playing with your dog... or can lose track of time while immersed in a good book. 

The you that's brave enough to show your vulnerabilities... because you know that's where your strength truly lies.

That's the stuff that doesn't fade. 

AND here's some science to back that up:

Research from the University of Rochester says deep emotional connection and shared values beat physical attractiveness in the long-run game of relationship satisfaction. 

Unfortunately... we've got it all backwards in our swipe-right culture. 

We're trained to notice the surface stuff first - the looks, the style, the charm - and focus mainly on this!

But those are merely the kindling for love. The real flame? That's your soul.

So if you're looking for love.. mindfully prioritize finding someone who's soul food... rather than prioritizing someone who's merely eye candy.

Share your thoughts below!

xo, Karen

Drop some 💖 for the power of love & understanding!

LOVE TIP 1: During a conflict with your partner, don't focus on "MUST WIN THIS ARGUMENT." Instead, focus on trying to "UNDERSTAND EACH OTHER BETTER." 

Oh & understanding isn’t about agreeing or changing your stance. It’s about acknowledging your partner's feelings, thoughts & viewpoints - letting them know they’re heard and their feelings are considered valid.

Bonus: Empathy is an aphrodisiac!

LOVE TIP 2: When initiating a difficult conversation, ditch the criticism. Instead, express your feelings using "I" statements, followed by a positive need. For example, rather than saying, "You never help with the dishes," try, "I feel overwhelmed doing the dishes alone, and I'd really appreciate your help." This technique minimizes defensiveness & helps your partner UNDERSTAND YOUR PERSPECTIVE... without feeling attacked. (Yep, there's that word "understand" again! )

FINAL LOVE TIP: The next time you're in a fight, remember - your goal isn't agreement, it's understanding. By striving for UNDERSTANDING, we create a safe space where love and respect can grow!

Spot a red flag? 

🛑 STOP: The moment you recognize a red flag, give yourself permission to pause. It's not about being overly critical, but about honoring your feelings and instincts.

📚 LEARN: Understand what this red flag means to you. Is it signaling a potential issue that could affect your peace, happiness, self worth or safety?

🤔 ASSESS: Take a step back and evaluate the situation objectively. Remember, red flags can sometimes be masked by our hopes, fears, traumas, or limited beliefs.

🗣️ COMMUNICATE: If appropriate and safe, discuss the issue openly and honestly with the red flag bearing person! They might not be aware of their red flag or how it's affecting you.

👣 ACT: Based on your understanding and communication, take the necessary steps. Whether it means creating boundaries or walking away! Act with courage and self respect!

Need more support to maintain stronger boundaries? See LINK in my BIO for free ebooks and online courses to help you to speak up - and boundary up!

I believe one of the most important qualities you should look for in a relationship is the feeling of "safety."

In fact, you should seek the feeling of “safety” even BEFORE the feeling of love.

Why?

Without the feeling of safety, you will NEVER arrive at feeling true intimate love — because you won’t allow yourself to be vulnerable enough for true intimacy.

And if you’re not your most vulnerable, authentic self with someone – then you’re not experiencing a true love connection. 

Plus... in a good relationship your partner should WANT to make you feel not only loved – but also safe.

Unfortunately many folks overly prioritize finding a partner who is…

sexy
smart
successful
funny

In so doing, they are even willing to put up with a partner who makes them feel UNSAFE – as long as this partner is sexy, smart, successful, funny, etc….

HOW TO LET THAT SHIT GO...

🌟 Reframe your past.. so you can release its grip, and embrace a brighter future! 

1️⃣ Acknowledge: Recognize that your past doesn't define you. It's a collection of experiences, but it doesn't determine your worth or potential.

2️⃣ Learn and Grow: Extract the valuable lessons from your past without dwelling on the pain. Use them as stepping stones for personal growth and wisdom.

3️⃣ Practice Forgiveness: Forgive yourself and do your best to forgive others. Holding onto grudges or guilt only prolongs the negative impact. 

4️⃣ Embrace Self-Compassion: Treat yourself with kindness and understanding. Understand that mistakes are part of being human. Be gentle with yourself as you navigate through the process of letting go.

5️⃣ Live in the Present: Focus on the present moment and all the opportunities it holds. Redirect your energy towards creating a fulfilling and joyful life right now.

6️⃣ Create a New Narrative: Rewrite your story and shape it in a way that empowers you. Replace self-limiting beliefs with positive affirmations that reflect your true potential.

7️⃣ Let Go: Release the grip of the past by consciously choosing to let it go. Allow yourself to move forward, unburdened by what no longer serves you.

Remember, the power to redefine your future lies within you. 🌈

A gentle reminder💗

You know that little voice that whispers worst-case scenarios in your ear? Yeah, we all have it. And if you're anything like me, you've probably had days where it feels like it's on repeat. 

Why? Because we've faced some of those worst moments and they've left their mark. 

So here are some tips to help...

🌅 Shift Your Focus: Instead of zooming in on what could go wrong, pan out to the broader picture of possibilities.

🌈 Celebrate Your Resilience: Remember all the times you bounced back? That's your superpower.

📘 Redirect the Narrative: Every time that voice starts, interrupt it with a positive story of "What if?"

Our brains are wired to protect us, and sometimes that means playing out every scary scenario. But just as we've learned to brace for the worst, we can also train ourselves to hope for the best. 

It takes practice, it takes intention, and sometimes it just takes taking a deep breath and reminding ourselves: "I've got this."

Because, my friend, you absolutely do.

Think about it. Before the digital age, where did all our spicy takes go? 

Just bouncing around in our heads? 

It's wild to consider that once upon a time, every heated opinion didn't get its 15 minutes of fame on the internet. 

Were we more at peace back then...? Or just silently fuming? 

Maybe there’s some wisdom in not sharing every rant. 

Still, it makes you appreciate the double-edged sword of technology. 

We can share, but should we always?

💪REMINDER: Pain, in its most piercing moments, strips away the superfluous, leaving us with the raw truth of who we are and what matters most. 

Pain, in its mysterious wisdom, forces us to reevaluate our lives, our choices, our connections.

It brings a clarity that often eludes us in our more complacent moments. 

We learn that our capacity for growth is not despite our pain... but because of it.

NEED SUPPORT?

🌼 Tip 1: Cultivate Self-Compassion Through Metaphor - Use metaphorical thinking, a tool often used in psychotherapy, to create distance and perspective. For example, imagine your pain as a wave. Observe it. Respect its power. But know that you are the shore it washes over, not the wave itself.

🌼 Tip 2: Practice Radical Acceptance - Accept your situation wholly, without resistance or judgment. This acceptance doesn’t mean defeat. It means acknowledging the reality of it - while embracing the inner will to work through things.

🌼Tip 3: Foster a Growth Mindset - View your struggles as opportunities to learn and grow. 

🌼 Tip 4: Find Solace in Artistic Expression - Channel your pain into a creative outlet -whether it's painting, writing, music, or dance, etc

🌼 Tip 5:  Grab my FREE Think Happy eBook - designed to offer comfort, insight, and direction during life’s turbulent times. See LINK in my @notsalmon bio!

➡️What’s the #1 reason for divorces & break ups? 
* Bad sex?
* Money issues?

Nope. It’s...

* Poor communication.

Meaning?

* You had poor communication when you chose your partner - which prevented you from fully recognizing WHO your partner was - beneath their sexy, appealing exterior.
* You had poor communication after getting into the relationship - which created a downward spiral of misunderstanding, escalated conflicts, disrespect, contempt, doom and gloom - beyond repair.

This is why I created my video course:

Broken Heart Recovery Course

(See link in my @notsalmon bio to learn more)

Basically…I wanted to share all of the many research-based relationship strategies I learned over the last few decades - to help you to...

* improve your communication while dating - plus give you a specific list of conversations to share with someone - so you can spot red flags sooner - and swerve away from narcissists, codependent relationships, unavailable partners etc…

* Improve your communication while in your relationship - plus give you helpful research based tools to nip conflicts in the bud - so you stop downward spiraling.

Most video courses on “healing from break ups” do NOT share these specific research-based communication tools!

But that’s not all!

My Broken Heart Recovery Course also helps you to...

* Gain clarity around subconscious limiting beliefs - which keep you stuck in the same bad love patterns

* Get stronger at spotting & avoiding narcissists, codependent partnerships, unavailable people, toxic partners of all kinds.

* Manage & release overwhelming emotions, fear and insecurity around love.

* Cut toxic cords to your ex – so you create more space to allow someone new & better

* Much more

My Broken Heart Recovery Course will...

* NOT ONLY help you to heal your broken heart!

* You’ll ALSO learn new ways of thinking and dating - so you can find and maintain a happier relationship!

Drop some 🛑⛔️🚫 for the power of pause.

Here's a 2-step tip to use THE POWER OF PAUSE in your day.

1️⃣ MORNING PAUSE: Every morning, look at your "to do list" and take a moment to really think about the power and worth of your energy. Think about what and who matters most to you. Think about your core values and biggest goals/dreams. Then learn to say that tongue twister of a word “no”!! Remember, you're not an unlimited cell phone plan. 📱

2️⃣ THE "RESPOND DON'T REACT" PAUSE: As new things come up throughout your day that stress you out ... pause... and really think about the best ways to respond. Be as picky with your words, thoughts and actions - as you are when you pick that perfect avocado at the grocery store. 🥑

I’ve found this to be true. You too? :)

Confession: I used to be a secret binge eater. While I was binging nothing else mattered. 
Food helped me to numb my uncomfortable emotions.

I’d feel good in the moment, but horrible afterwards.

After a binge, I felt a lot of shame, regret & anger at myself. Plus I felt uncomfortable in my body.

My worst time with binging was when I was pregnant. Unfortunately I wound up gaining 90 pounds on my 5 foot 3 frame. And, no, I was not pregnant with a teenager.

Looking back I realize I had a true food addiction. I was using pregnancy as an excuse to binge eat. And I continued to binge eat after my son was born.

A health scare snapped me out of my binge eating. My doctor called to tell me my health was in danger.So I decided to get to the root of my binging.

I knew that going on another diet wouldn’t help – because it was not WHAT I was eating that was my problem.

It was WHY I was overeating.

I needed to understand the WHY behind my binge eating & face underlying eating issues.

So I went into research geek mode. I read piles of studies on binge eating, body dysmorphia – etc

Thankfully I stopped binging w/ the help of a range of research-backed tools:

* Thought Mastery Techniques
* NLP strategies
* Cognitive Dissonance tricks
* Guided Meditations
* “Pause Buttons” to snap me out of reactive mode

Pretty soon, food lost its power over me & I lost 20 pounds in 3 months. I’ve kept the weight off for a decade+!

So I created a convenient video course...
=> Stop Emotional Eating <= 

SEE LINK IN MY @NOTSALMON BIO FOR INFO!

Already my course has helped many thousands of people around the world to FINALLY break unhealthy eating patterns.

Stop Emotional Eating is NOT a diet program. It’s a permanent habit changing program!

Learn how to…

* Eat only when you’re hungry
* Lose interest in food when full
* Leave food on your plate because you recognize you’re full
* Start choosing to destress in healthier ways than stress eating
* Be at your body’s healthy weight without dieting
* Feel confident not only in your body – but in who you are.

SEE LINK IN @NOTSALMON BIO FOR INFO ABOUT MY STOP EMOTIONAL EATING COURSE.

"So often, children are punished for being human. Children are not allowed to have grumpy moods, bad days, disrespectful tones, or bad attitudes, yet we adults have them all the time! We think if we don't nip it in the bud, it will escalate and we will lose control. Let go of that unfounded fear and give your child permission to be human. We all have days like that. None of us are perfect, and we must stop holding our kids to a higher standard of perfection than we can attain ourselves. All of the punishments you could throw at them won't stamp out their humanity, for to err is human & we all do it." -  Rebecca Eanes

🌟 5 Steps to Clear Your Mental Clutter! 🧹✨

1️⃣ Acknowledge What’s Out of Your Control: Identify the thoughts and worries that are beyond your control. Recognize that dwelling on them only drains your energy.

2️⃣ Embrace the Power of Letting Go: Practice acceptance and release what you can’t control. Understand that it’s okay to redirect your focus towards more productive and positive thoughts.

3️⃣ Engage in Mindful Activities: Engross yourself in activities that bring you joy and create a sense of flow. Whether it’s painting, dancing, or hiking in nature, find what helps you detach from unhelpful thoughts.

4️⃣ Journal Your Worries Away: Write down your concerns, fears, and frustrations. This act of externalizing your thoughts can provide clarity and free up mental space for more constructive thinking.
